"rating":"4.5",
"reviewcomment":"Three Michelin stars.  Four-star rating by the New York Times.  Simply put, Le Bernardin is the standard-bearer of the New York City fine dining scene.  Though the restaurant specializes in French cuisine, its theme is summed up perfectly by its executive chef and co-owner, Eric Ripert, who noted that at Le Bernardin, &#34;the fish is the star.&#34;  Indeed, what sets this establishment apart is its mastery of piscine preparation.  Rather than overwhelming fish with salt and flavor, which seems to be the norm nowadays, the chefs at Le Bernardin exquisitely draw out the natural flavor of the fish with more subtle tastes.  <br><br>I visited during lunch hours and sat in the Lounge, which features a very reasonable $45 three-course prix fixe menu in addition to the standard fare.  The sea scallops, which were thinly sliced and dressed with extra virgin olive oil, chives, and lemon, were phenomenal.  For my main course, I chose the merluza, a flaky cod-like fish (I had no idea what it was either until I looked it up before ordering) that was served with a parsnip purée with a perfectly understated dijon mustard sherry emulsion.  In keeping with the restaurant&#39;s French tradition, the saucing for the fish was applied at the table.  It was simply perfect.  The disassembled Mascarpone Mousse served as the perfect ending to the meal.    <br><br>As is expected of restaurants in this class, the service was impeccable.  Multiple waiters coordinated their movements to refill our drinks, replace utensils, and otherwise keep us satisfied.  A final thought: the impossibly wide array of selections in the bread basket might be irresistable (I would highly recommend the tomato fennel or the rosemary focaccia), but don&#39;t be an amateur and fill yourself up with bread!",
