"rating":"4.5",
"reviewcomment":"Sushi Azabu has been on my &#34;to eat&#34; list for maybe one and a half years. I finally was able to pencil in some time, make the trek and come out to Tribeca for a nice Valentine&#39;s dinner with my honey pie. Best sushi I&#39;ve had since Sushi Yasuda which was a year ago.<br><br>ATMOSPHERE:<br>It&#39;s a little confusing as Azabu is combined with Greenwich Grill in terms of the ground floor being Greenwich grill and the basement being Sushi Azabu. They are both obviously owned by the same owner but if one did not know that, it could be hard to find as you go through Greenwich to get to Sushi Azabu. Sushi Azabu has wood veneer, very small space which makes for intimacy, however you can get sort of cozy with your neighbor. It is definitely for a party of 2 and I would not recommend coming with any larger. Date place for sure. We did not get to sit at the bar but that is the route I would recommend if you can get that seat. <br><br>SERVICE:<br>Very cordial and nice. You can&#39;t go wrong if you have a small space to service. <br><br>FOOD:<br>We were here for the Valentine&#39;s prefix but the Omakase is very good I hear. I&#39;d imagine the Valentine&#39;s is very similar to that. The sushi was so tender and literally melted in your mouth. Wow. Some of our favorites included the Uni appetizer and their black sesame dessert which was to die for. As for sushi/sashimi, I would recommend the shrimp, uni, fatty tuna and bbq eel. They were the most delicious, flavorful and I could not stop salivating to eat them as we saved them for last. The black sesame dessert was VERY good as well and I inhaled it like no tomorrow. <br><br>SUMMARY:<br>Want a nice date night in Tribeca and craving sushi? Then look no further. Perfect place to go and don&#39;t forget to get the shrimp/uni/fatty tuna and the black sesame dessert. Greenwich Grill up top looks like a great alternative if you can&#39;t get reservations and don&#39;t mind Japanese fusion. I&#39;m sure it&#39;s just as mind blowing.",
